# Code Review Guidelines

**Activation Mode:** Model Decision
**Description:** Apply when reviewing code, identifying issues, and providing feedback for NestJS applications

## Review Criteria

### Code Standards
- Check for adherence to NestJS coding standards and conventions
- Verify TypeScript types are properly defined and used
- Ensure proper use of decorators and metadata
- Verify consistent naming conventions throughout
- Check for proper file organization and module structure

### Architecture Review
- Validate proper use of NestJS module system
- Check for appropriate separation of concerns (controllers, services, repositories)
- Verify dependency injection is used correctly
- Ensure proper module imports and exports
- Review layered architecture adherence

## TypeScript Review

### Type Safety
- Verify all functions have proper return type annotations
- Check for proper use of interfaces vs types
- Ensure DTOs are properly typed and validated
- Look for any usage of 'any' type (should be avoided)
- Verify generic types are used appropriately

### Decorator Usage
- Verify proper use of NestJS decorators
- Check for correct parameter decorators (@Body, @Param, @Query)
- Ensure validation decorators are applied to DTOs
- Verify Swagger decorators are present for API documentation

## Controllers Review

### Best Practices
- Verify controllers are thin and delegate to services
- Check for proper HTTP method decorators
- Ensure DTOs are used for request/response
- Verify proper error handling
- Check for appropriate use of Guards and Interceptors

### Route Design
- Review RESTful route design
- Check for consistent route naming
- Verify proper HTTP status codes
- Ensure route versioning if applicable

## Services Review

### Business Logic
- Verify business logic is in services, not controllers
- Check for single responsibility principle adherence
- Ensure proper error handling and exception throwing
- Verify transaction management where needed
- Check for proper async/await usage

### Dependency Management
- Review constructor injection usage
- Check for circular dependencies
- Verify proper scope usage (singleton, request, transient)
- Ensure interfaces are used for abstractions

## Data Layer Review

### DTOs
- Verify validation decorators are present
- Check for proper use of PartialType, PickType, OmitType
- Ensure separate DTOs for create, update, and response
- Verify transformation decorators if needed

### Entities
- Check for proper relationship definitions
- Verify cascade options are appropriate
- Ensure indexes are defined for frequently queried fields
- Check for proper use of timestamps

### Repository Usage
- Verify custom repositories extend TypeORM Repository
- Check for proper query optimization
- Ensure parameterized queries (no SQL injection risks)
- Verify transaction handling for complex operations

## Security Review

### Authentication & Authorization
- Verify Guards are applied to protected routes
- Check for proper JWT validation
- Ensure role-based access control is implemented correctly
- Verify password hashing (bcrypt/argon2)

### Input Validation
- Ensure all inputs are validated using DTOs
- Check for SQL injection prevention
- Verify XSS prevention measures
- Check for proper sanitization

### Configuration & Secrets
- Verify no hardcoded secrets or credentials
- Check for proper use of ConfigService
- Ensure environment variables are validated
- Verify sensitive data is not logged

### Rate Limiting & Throttling
- Check for rate limiting on public endpoints
- Verify throttling configuration
- Ensure CORS is properly configured
- Check for Helmet usage for security headers

## Performance Review

### Database Optimization
- Review query efficiency
- Check for N+1 query problems
- Verify proper use of indexes
- Ensure pagination for large datasets
- Check for lazy vs eager loading appropriateness

### Caching
- Review caching strategy
- Check for cache invalidation logic
- Verify cache key naming conventions
- Ensure appropriate TTL values

### Resource Management
- Check for proper cleanup in lifecycle hooks
- Verify connection pooling configuration
- Ensure no memory leaks in subscriptions
- Review file upload size limits

## Error Handling Review

### Exception Handling
- Verify proper use of NestJS exception classes
- Check for meaningful error messages
- Ensure errors are logged appropriately
- Verify global exception filter usage

### Error Responses
- Check for consistent error response format
- Verify appropriate HTTP status codes
- Ensure error details don't leak sensitive information
- Check for proper error logging

## Testing Review

### Test Coverage
- Verify unit tests exist for services
- Check for controller tests
- Ensure e2e tests for critical paths
- Verify test naming conventions

### Test Quality
- Check for proper mocking of dependencies
- Verify tests are independent
- Ensure both success and failure cases are tested
- Check for edge case coverage

## Code Quality

### Readability
- Assess code readability and maintainability
- Check for proper comments on complex logic
- Verify consistent code formatting
- Ensure meaningful variable and function names

### Code Smells
- Look for duplicated code
- Check for overly complex functions (cyclomatic complexity)
- Identify long parameter lists
- Look for large classes/services that need refactoring

### Documentation
- Verify JSDoc comments on public methods
- Check for README updates if needed
- Ensure Swagger documentation is complete
- Verify changelog updates for significant changes

## Module Organization

### Structure
- Verify proper module hierarchy
- Check for circular module dependencies
- Ensure shared modules are properly exported
- Verify dynamic modules are implemented correctly

### Imports
- Check for unnecessary imports
- Verify barrel exports are used
- Ensure proper re-exports in modules
- Check for unused dependencies

## Configuration Review

### Environment Configuration
- Verify proper use of @nestjs/config
- Check for configuration validation
- Ensure environment-specific configurations
- Verify default values are provided

### Application Configuration
- Check for proper global pipe configuration
- Verify global interceptor setup
- Ensure global filter configuration
- Review middleware configuration

## Logging Review

### Logger Usage
- Verify Logger service is used instead of console.log
- Check for appropriate log levels
- Ensure sensitive data is not logged
- Verify request/response logging configuration

## API Design Review

### REST API
- Verify RESTful principles are followed
- Check for proper resource naming
- Ensure consistent response formats
- Verify proper use of HTTP methods

### GraphQL (if applicable)
- Check resolver implementation
- Verify proper query/mutation structure
- Ensure proper type definitions
- Check for N+1 query prevention (DataLoader)

## Feedback Guidelines

### Constructive Feedback
- Provide specific, actionable feedback
- Suggest improvements with reasoning
- Include code examples for suggested changes
- Highlight both positive aspects and areas for improvement
- Focus on the code, not the person

### Priority Levels
- Critical: Security issues, bugs, data loss risks
- High: Performance issues, architectural problems
- Medium: Code quality, maintainability concerns
- Low: Style preferences, minor optimizations

## Common Issues Checklist

- [ ] No hardcoded credentials or secrets
- [ ] Proper error handling and logging
- [ ] Input validation on all endpoints
- [ ] Proper TypeScript typing (no 'any')
- [ ] Security headers configured
- [ ] Authentication/Authorization properly implemented
- [ ] Database queries optimized
- [ ] Proper transaction handling
- [ ] Tests cover critical functionality
- [ ] API documentation up to date
- [ ] No circular dependencies
- [ ] Proper module organization
- [ ] Environment variables validated
- [ ] Migrations for database changes
